third to four and a half times in length from snout to vent. Tail is shorter than head and body. Habitat: This species inhabits areas characterised by damp ground. Arnold (1980, 1984) indicates that this species is secretive but abundant in planta- tions and cultivated areas where the ground is damp. Furthermore, it inhabits buildings and gardens where it was observed under leaves (Amr et al., 2021). Biology: This species feeds on insect larvae, coleopterans and orthopterans. Remarks: This species was not listed by Eissa and El Assy (1975). Reptiles and amphibians of Kuwait 75 Figure 52: Arabian sand skink, Scincus mitranus (Photo by", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "651f3216-47c9-4210-ba99-d73c8de2bd15": {"__data__": {"id_": "651f3216-47c9-4210-ba99-d73c8de2bd15", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/reptiles-and-amphibians-state-kuwait", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Reptiles and amphibians of the State of Kuwait", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/reptiles-and-amphibians-state-kuwait", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "34a40bca9aa0cb5e8715a7b4f2ad453af95c26ae59674f8ec70a878643fafab5"}, "3": {"node_id": "61a9886e-c0e5-4dab-840e-a9245452994e", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/reptiles-and-amphibians-state-kuwait", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conserva