l support for entre- preneurship, Kenya shows immense prom- ise around innovation and new ventures, as evidenced by the World Economic Forum flagging Kenya as an \u201cemerging global start- up hotspot.\u201d5 Kenya is actively prioritizing startup ventures through its Enterprise Kenya program, the government\u2019s \u201cnational accelerator to catalyse innovations and pro- vide entrepreneurs with needed support in Introduction 2 Blue entrepreneurship scoping study in Kenya their innovation journey.\u201d6 Additionally, the amount of funding toward startups and the number of investments shows a continued increase from previous years, with Kenya benefitting from US$564 million in invest- ment funding in 2019, ranked second across the African continent behind Nigeria only.7 While still battling some of the challenges common to lower middle-income econo- mies, Kenya showcases that its startup envi- ronment is conducive and can be expected to grow ocean ventures. The potential to drive impact among coastal communities grows year-on-year, as a combination of factors highlights Blue Entrepreneurship as a key driver. For example, global demand for ocean-based and ocean-adjacent products and services continues to grow, due to a rising global population8 who need inexpensive protein sources,9,10 an increasing middle-class inter- ested in travel,11 and a growing proportion of world tourism being dedicated to \u201cemerging markets.\u201d12 Kenya benefits from both of these sectors, with 0.8%13 of national gross domes- tic product (GDP) dedicated to fisheries and 6 ICT Authority. (n.d.). Enterprise Kenya. https://icta.go.ke/enterprise-kenya/ 7 Partech Africa. (2020). 2019 Africa Tech Venture Capital Report. https://cdn-website.partechpartners.com/media/ documents/2020.01_Partech_Africa_-_2019_Africa_Tech_VC_Report_FINAL.pdf 8 United Nations (UN). (n.d.). Global Issues: Population. https://www.un.org/en/global-issues/population 9 The World Bank Group, Agriculture And Environme